The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Kannur, Feb. 20 (PTI): An 18-year-old schoolgirl and her lover allegedly committed suicide after video clippings of her kissing a classmate were posted on the Internet, police in Kerala said today.          
	The girl, a Class XII student, and a 27-year-old plumber, believed to be her boyfriend, were found hanging from a tree, the police said. The video recorded by another student on a cellphone was circulated as MMS and uploaded on the Internet. The school has banned use of mobiles after the incident.                  
	Shimla (PTI): Himachal Pradesh High Court on Saturday announced that a special green bench would start functioning in the state from next week every Friday to deal with cases related to environment, mines and forests and hydro-power projects.                   
	Mumbai (PTI): NCP chief Sharad Pawar on Saturday shared the stage with suspended member and Osmanabad MP Padamsinh Patil at a party meeting. Patil is accused in a murder case. Pawar also told Patils son not to lose heart over his defeat in the October polls.                   
	Mumbai (PTI): The hearing on the 26/11 terror case was on Saturday adjourned till Monday after the prosecution sought permission to submit affidavits of another 44 witnesses.                   
	Nagpur (PTI): A 54-year-old track supervisor was crushed to death on Friday by a Rajdhani Express in Nagpur division of Central Railway here, police said. He had alerted others when he saw a goods train coming. But because of the loud noise, he could not hear the express approaching.                   
	 Lucknow (PTI): The Uttar Pradesh government will give up to Rs 25 lakh as reward to people who alert authorities about drug rackets. It has also amended laws to punish those involved in making spurious drugs with jail terms ranging from 10 years to life and a fine of Rs 10 lakh.                                                                                                                                               
